Dr. Leslie Harris, polychaete expert, remarks: "different NEP websites & publications report this soft-sediment worm as both M. infundibulum & M. aesthetica, which is the first part of the confusion. In Europe M. infundibulum is found in soft-sediments & M. aesthetica is the one hanging from docks & hard-surfaces so if our NEP specimens are really the same as a European species they would be M. infundibulum. However, our NEP specimens are distinctly different both morphologically & genetically from infundibulum. The second part of the confusion is what to call them. In the past several NEP species of Myxicola were described from California, Puget Sound, & Alaska. All of the original specimens need to be re-examined so we can decide what name (or names) to use in the NEP."

Didemnum spp. in our dive log data for Galiano Island is most likely via our Didemnun/Trididemnum category. This category has traditionally been used for encrusting whitish compound tunicate that often forms large sheets . We have followed this procedure based upon Gretchen Lambert's advice. An impossible task to go further in the field and without specimen sampling.

Requires review; confer with Gretchen Lambert; the Didemnum vexillum name is the result of a recent interaction with Gretchen Lambert. This is the correct name for the invasive species shown in our book (page 357, CH43) which was tentatively termed Didemnum.

Andy Lamb: "With respect to Hydractinia sp./Hydractinia cf. aggregata: This Hydractinia sp. was used in our database for "snail fur hydroid"; Jensen et al, 2018, page 36, shows two species Schuchertinia allmani and Clavactinia serrata that essentially speak to what we have done historically. For sure our records would include the latter but also most likely the latter. Perhaps Henry could advise on this? Or perhaps there is photographic evidence available (Charlie/Neil or others)? As a fall back, I would be confident in listing the former but not for sure the latter based upon our records." Henry Choong: “I can only answer your question very generally, as I haven’t seen the specimen to which you refer. Hydractinia aggregata is still a valid species. The arrangement of the tentacles will help you distinguish between Clavactinia and Hydractinia. Some Hydractinia spp. are now included in Schuchertinia S. allmani is circum-arctic. In any case the genus Schuchertinia has no diagnostic morphological characters except for the presence of fixed gonophores (with one exception). Schuchertinia allmani and Clavactinia serrataa are not synonymous. I cannot say anything specific to your specimen as I have not seen it.”
Andy Lamb: "With respect to Hydractinia sp, vs Hydractinia cf. laevispina -- our data base and Jensen et al, 2018 use the former"
